  "body": "**What happened**:\r\nWhile I was reading the autoscaling source code, I found the method calculateScaleUpLimitWithScalingRules in kube-controller-manager/app/autoscaling.go has a bug if we set SelectPolicy MinPolicySelect. Since the default variable result is 0, the final result would be 0 because the min selectPolicyFn. I'm not sure if it is the expected result, but from my perspective, the result value should be the minimal value among all the proposed value and the initial result value should not be counted.\r\n\r\nIf it is a bug, I'm interested to fix it ^_^\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nIf the the currentReplica = 5, replicasAddedInCurrentPeriod =0, policy.Value is 1. the expected result variable value should be 6, however, it is 0\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\nJust as the `What you expected to happen` says\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\n- OS (e.g: `cat /etc/os-release`):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Network plugin and version (if this is a network-related bug):\r\n- Others:\r\n",
